===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# {{context|theology}} The [[doctrine]] that each individual human [[soul]] is [[create]]d by God in Christianity, Judaism, Islam and the Baha'i Faith, as opposed to [[traducianism]].
#* {{quote-book|title=The Doctrine of the Incarnation of our Lord Jesus Christ, in its relation to Mankind and to the Church|author=[[w:Robert Isaac Wilberforce|Robert Wilberforce]]|year=1848|passage=the preservation of the race of man is made to grow out of that quickening impulse, which we call the life of humanity. This notion, which was called Traducianism by the schoolmen (the system opposed to it being termed '''Creatianism''' {{SIC}})}}
# Any creationary [[belief]], especially a belief that the origin of things is due to an event or process of creation brought about by the deliberate act of any divine agency, such as a [[Creator]] [[God]] ([[creator]] [[god]]).
# The belief that a deity created the world, especially as described in a particular religious text, such as the Book of [[Genesis]].
#* {{quote-book|title=Natural science and religion, 2 lectures‎|page=89|author=[[w:Asa Gray|Asa Gray]]|year=1880|passage=It must be reasonably clear to all who have taken pains to understand the matter that the true issue as regards design is not between Darwinism and direct '''Creationism''', but between design and fortuity, between any intention or intellectual cause and no intention nor predicable first cause.}}

